{
  "summary": "I reviewed controllers/settle.go (SettleLeases) and its wiring through Bridge.WithWorld/reportSweep, tracing Bridge.load, the NodeReconciler fencing verdict, cleanupDeletedRun, releaseRun/completeRun, the RunReference type, the plugin's PreBind mint (admission.PodLeaseWithRole), and the invariant oracle. I did not speculate: I built a scratch module with a replace directive against /workspaces/jobtree and exercised both the pure engine (controllers.SettleLeases over a ClusterState) and the real controllers/kube.Bridge over a controller-runtime fake client. The core sweep logic is sound against sole-committer states and against the cross-process plugin race: because a Run causally precedes its pods and its leases by many reconcile cycles, because each APIReader List is individually consistent, because terminal is a stable phase, and because a lease-create event always re-triggers a WithWorld pass whose sweep re-closes it, I could NOT construct a state where the sweep destroys a live, sole-committer-funded run's work or leaves an immortal lease via the plugin race — it heals those races rather than causing them. I DID confirm one concrete way it destroys something it should not: an empty-valued run-name label (which client.HasLabels admits into the world) collapses to the doomed key \"namespace/\" and makes the sweep silently delete that pod through the API and close any empty-RunRef lease, accusing nobody. Its blast radius is confined to malformed, non-sole-committer objects. I also confirmed the terminal-run panic path is effectively redundant with the engine's deferred oracle (which fires first on the identical predicate), so Q3's envtest-flake fear is unfounded, and I flag a pre-existing name-only-RunRef immortal-lease that the orphan rule advertises but structurally cannot cover.",
  "answers": {
    "1. SettleLeases derives `doomed` from state.Runs (terminal) and from leases+pods whose run key is ABSENT from state.Runs. Bridge.load lists Runs with APIReader (uncached). Enumerate every way state.Runs can be missing a Run that actually exists...": "Traced Bridge.load (bridge.go:168-262). It issues six SEPARATE uncached APIReader.List calls (Runs first at :170, Leases at :178, Pods at :190) with NO namespace/field selector, so they are not one transaction. List errors are NOT swallowed: every List returns `fmt.Errorf(...)` up through WithWorld, aborting the pass before any sweep. Pagination is not a gap: the Lists set no Limit, so the apiserver returns the full collection with no continue token. The direct APIReader is cluster-scoped (it bypasses the cache), so no manager namespace filter applies; a namespace/RBAC restriction would surface as a 403 error (returned), not a silent subset. The one theoretical miss — a Run listed-before-it-existed while its lease/pod is listed-after — is causally unreachable: a lease exists only after the bridge created the pod and the plugin minted at PreBind, which is seconds-to-minutes after the Run was created and reconciled, so any Run whose lease is visible was created well before List Runs. Conclusion: the orphan rule fires only for GENUINELY deleted Runs (correct cleanup); it cannot orphan a live Run.",
    "2. The plugin mints a Lease at PreBind, concurrently with the controller process. Construct the interleaving... Is that correct, or does it kill a pod the plugin has just funded? Now the reverse... What closes THAT lease? Is it immortal?": "Forward case: Run R goes Failed while the plugin binds a straggler pod P and mints lease L for it after the failRun pass loaded its snapshot; the next WithWorld loads R=Failed + open L + P, and the terminal-run sweep closes L and deletes P. This is CORRECT — R is genuinely dead (gang co-terminates), so L would otherwise be an immortal lease and P a zombie container; settle heals it. It is flagged Shirked (a terminal-run closure) which panics under test but only logs+heals in production. Reverse case is NOT immortal: after the sweep closes L1/drops P, if the plugin mints L2 for P, the L2 create fires leaseToRun -> RunReconciler -> WithWorld, and because R stays terminal (or absent), that pass's sweep closes L2; every subsequent mint re-triggers the same closing pass, and once P is deleted the scheduler stops binding and the plugin stops minting, so it converges. Settle is the mechanism that PREVENTS the immortal lease here, not one that creates it.",
